ce:section.ce:para:
The analytical performance of the fluorescent probe was evaluated by responding to DA. Fig. 3
                        a showed the fluorescence intensity decreased with DA concentration gradually increased. The DA concentration were linear over the range 0.25–30 μM with a regression equation of F/F0 = 0.97079-0.01877C (Fig. 3b), where C stands for the concentration of DA (μM), R2 = 0.99609 and LOD = 0.0972 μM (S/N = 3). However, as shown in Fig. S2, the relationship of the F/F0 and the concentration of DA in a wider range was well described by an exponential function (F/F0 = 0.2324 + 0.73814/(1+(C/17.45164)1.565), 0.25–100 μM, R2 = 0.99733). Compared with other reported literatures (Table 1
                        ) [14,36–41], this sensor is ecofriendly and simple. In addition, the proposed method has a low LOD and wide linear range compared with most of the reported works. To evaluate the specificity of the method, fluorescence intensity of N-CQDs in the presence of biomolecules such as l-Cys, Gly, Glucose, l-phe, AA, EP, UA, l-Ala, l-Ser, l-Asp, l-Lys, Glu and metal ions including K+, Na+, Mg2+, and Ca2+ were investigated. As shown in Fig. 3c, fluorescence quenching of N-CQDs was only induced by the DA compared with the other samples at the same concentration (1 mM). Moreover, the co-existence of other analytes with dopamine did not affect the quenching results of the probe. The corresponding fluorescence spectrum was shown in Fig. S3.
